<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The defining climate-policy distinction. Today: draft your Brief's Recommendations.</p>
  <p><strong>Mitigation</strong> = reduce the cause (cut emissions). <strong>Adaptation</strong> = reduce the impact (build resilience to changes already locked in). Both matter, but Chennai (as a city government, not a national one) has far more <em>adaptation</em> levers than mitigation levers. National policy decides on power plants and fuel taxes. The Greater Chennai Corporation decides on drainage, building codes, cooling shelters, mangrove restoration. Data centers belong on this list too — Chennai is a growing data-center hub, and their cooling draws on the same stressed water system the rest of the city shares; the demand side of Block 4's story becomes an adaptation question here.</p>
  <p>The bell ringer makes the distinction visible: two Chennai billboards, side-by-side. One says "Plant a tree, save the planet." The other says "New AC subsidies for low-income households during heat waves." One is mitigation; one is adaptation. Both could be in the same year's budget. Today you internalize the distinction, then apply it to YOUR challenge by drafting the <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Brief's Recommendations section</a> — 3-5 specific, evidence-anchored, actionable items.</p>
</section>

